Analyzing the 2019 Stack Overflow Developer Survey Results using CRISP-DM¶

Link to my medium-blog-post: https://medium.com/@robertbemmann/applying-crisp-dm-on-the-2019-stack-overflow-developer-survey-dataset-a651c8da5baf

The cross-industry standard process for data mining or in short CRISP DM is an open standard process model that describes common approaches used by data mining experts. It is the most widely-used analytics model. source: Wikipedia

In order to demonstrate how CRISP DM works in practice, I'm going to apply the approach to a real-world example. I have chosen the Stack Overflow Annual Developer Survey dataset from 2019.

CRISP DM usually follows a 6-steps approach consisting of:

  • Business Understanding
  • Data Understanding
  • Prepare Data
  • Data Modeling
  • Evaluate the Results
  • Deploy

1. Business Understanding¶

The first part is about asking relevant questions regarding a topic from a business perspective.

The Stack Overflow Developer Survey is an annual survey among employees, specialists or enthusiasts within the IT and Computer Science field conducted by the Q&A site for professional and enthusiast programmers Stack Overflow. For the scope of this project, I am particularly interested in the following questions regarding the dataset of 2019:

1. Which type of developers has the highest compensation in Europe?
2. Is there a difference in compensation between Europe and the USA?
3. What languages and databases do data professionals work with most? Which ones are in the highest demand according to compensation?

2. Data Understanding¶

In this step, we need to familiarize with the data and translate the business questions into data questions. Sticking to the example we need to find out which columns of the dataset are relevant/helpful to answer the business questions.

1. Which type of developers has the highest compensation in Europe?

  • columns DevType, CurrencySymbol and ConvertedComp

2. Is there a difference in compensation between Europe and the USA?

  • columns CurrencySymbol and ConvertedComp

3. What languages and databases do data professionals work with most? Which ones are in the highest demand according to compensation?

  • columns LanguageWorkedWith, DatabaseWorkedWith and ConvertedComp

Additionally, it helps a lot to do the following at the beginning of data exploration:

  • Look at the number of rows and columns in the dataset
  • Check if there are missing values in any of the rows or columns
  • Check if any columns are of different data types than you would expect (ex: numbers showing as strings)
  • Build exploratory plots like bar charts, histograms, and scatterplots to better understand the data

3. Prepare Data¶

1. Which type of developers has the highest compensation in Europe?
2. Is there a difference in compensation between Europe and the USA?

In order to get answers for question 1 and 2, we need to do several cleaning and preparation steps.

We need to get a list of unique DevType's first. Also we are not really interested in Students and want to filter out the nan values. As participants can select multiple DevType's, we need to clean the data up.

In [9]:
def get_unique_values_list(column_name):
    '''
    INPUT:
    column_name - a string which matches a column name of the SO survey dataframe
    
    OUTPUT:
    output_list - a list of strings which contains all unique values of the input column 
    
    Description:
    The function takes the name of a column of the SO survey dataframe and creates a Series 
    (datatype string) with unique values from the dataframe subset of the respective column.
    Then the unique values row values are splitted by ';' and each piece is added to a list
    in case it is not already part of the list. Eventually, the list is returned.
    '''
    all_values_list = df[column_name].astype(str).unique()
    output_list = []
    for row in all_values_list:
        for entry in row.split(';'):
            if entry in output_list:
                True
            else:
                output_list.append(entry)
    return output_list

all_dev_types_list = get_unique_values_list('DevType')
print(all_dev_types_list)

def create_dev_type_metrics_df(input_df):
    '''
    INPUT:
    input_df - the name of a dataframe (can be subset) of the SO survey data
    
    OUTPUT:
    df_dev_type_metrics - dataframe with aggregated metrics per developer type
    for reporting purposes
    total_count - the total count of all dev_type occurences
    
    Description:
    The function takes a dataframe of the SO survey raw data (or a subset) and
    returns after a few transformations a dataframe with aggregated metrics
    per developer type like median of compensation, avg. years of professional 
    coding experience and the count per developer type. Furthermore an integer
    number of the total count is returned.
    '''
    list_dev_type = []
    list_median_comp = []
    list_avg_prf_exp = []
    list_count_dev_type = []

    for dev_type in all_dev_types_list:
        list_dev_type.append(dev_type)
        list_median_comp.append(input_df['ConvertedComp'][input_df['dev_type_'+dev_type] == 1].median())
        list_avg_prf_exp.append(input_df['YearsCodePro'][input_df['dev_type_'+dev_type] == 1].astype(float).mean(skipna=True))
        list_count_dev_type.append(input_df['dev_type_'+dev_type][input_df['dev_type_'+dev_type] == 1].count())
    
    df_dev_type_metrics = pd.DataFrame({'dev_type': list_dev_type,
                                        'compensation_median': list_median_comp,
                                        'prf_exp_mean': list_avg_prf_exp,
                                        'devtype_count': list_count_dev_type})

    total_count = df_dev_type_metrics['devtype_count'].sum() 
    
    return df_dev_type_metrics, total_count

def plots_for_data_professionals(job):
    '''
    INPUT:
    job - a string of a data professional job: ['Data or business analyst', 
    'Data scientist or machine learning specialist', 'Database administrator',
    'Engineer, data']
    
    OUTPUT:
    df_data_guys_metrics - dataframe with aggregated metrics per database 
    system or programming language for reporting purposes
    
    Description:
    The function takes a string of a data professional job and returns after 
    a few transformations a dataframe with aggregated metrics  of a subset 
    of the SO survey raw dataframe per database system or programming language
    like median of compensation and the count.
    '''
    list_language_db = []
    list_language_db_count = []
    list_language_db_comp_median = []

    for language in all_languages_list:
        list_language_db.append(language)
        list_language_db_count.append(df['dev_type_'+dev_type][(df['language_'+language] == 1) &
                                                           (df['dev_type_'+job]==1)]\
                                                           .count())
        list_language_db_comp_median.append(df['ConvertedComp'][(df['language_'+language] == 1) &
                                                            (df['dev_type_'+job]==1)]\
                                                            .median())
    
    #for dev_type in data_guys:
    for db in all_dbs_list:   
        list_language_db.append(db)
        list_language_db_count.append(df['dev_type_'+dev_type][(df['db_'+db] == 1) &
                                                               (df['dev_type_'+job]==1)]\
                                                               .count())
        list_language_db_comp_median.append(df['ConvertedComp'][(df['db_'+db] == 1) &
                                                               (df['dev_type_'+job]==1)]\
                                                               .median())

    df_data_guys_metrics = pd.DataFrame({'language_db': list_language_db,
                                     'language_db_count': list_language_db_count, 
                                     'language_db_comp_median':list_language_db_comp_median})
    # plot dbs used
    df_data_guys_metrics[(df_data_guys_metrics['language_db'].isin(all_dbs_list))].\
                            sort_values('language_db_count', ascending=False).\
                            plot(x='language_db', y='language_db_count', kind='barh',
                                 figsize=(10,6), color='b', alpha=0.4, title='Use of database systems for '+job);
    plt.xlabel("Frequency");
    plt.ylabel("Database");
    
    # plot languages used
    df_data_guys_metrics[(df_data_guys_metrics['language_db'].isin(all_languages_list))].\
                            sort_values('language_db_count', ascending=False).\
                            plot(x='language_db', y='language_db_count', kind='barh',
                                 figsize=(10,6), color='b', alpha=0.4, title='Use of programming languages for '+job);
    plt.xlabel("Frequency");
    plt.ylabel("Programming Language");

    return df_data_guys_metrics
